		"title" : "Tal.ki sees a 40% increase in website logins with Janrain Engage",
		"link" : "http://www.janrain.comblogs/talki-sees-40-increase-login-janrain-engage",
		"creator" : "Vincent Lauria",
		"description" : "<p><img alt=%34Tal.ki uses Janrain Engage%34 src=%34%2fsites%2fdefault%2ffiles%2fpartner-talki.png%34 style=%34padding-top%3a 0px; padding-right%3a 0px; padding-bottom%3a 20px; padding-left%3a 20px; float%3a right; width%3a 150px; height%3a 87px; %34 %2f><%2fp>				
											<p><em>Our partner, Vincent Lauria of Tal.ki, contributed this post for today%3a<%2fem><%2fp>				
											<p>	We%38#39;ve been running on the <a href=%34%2fjanrain-products-overview%34>Janrain platform<%2fa> for over half a year now. We use <a href=%34%2fproducts%2fengage%34>Janrain Engage<%2fa> to allow for third-party logins, such as Facebook, Twitter, Google, etc. When we first built our product, <a href=%34http%3a%2f%2ftal.ki%2f%34 target=%34_blank%34>Tal.ki Embeddable Forums<%2fa>, we made the%38nbsp;conscious%38nbsp;decision to not build our own user login system, we wanted to go the third-party route, this had two advantages%3a<%2fp>				
											<ol>				
											<li>Less development time to get to market<%2fli>				
											<li>A seamless experience for forums embedded across thousands of sites, no need to signup and create a new profile each time, just hop in and join the conversation.<%2fli>				
											<%2fol>				
											<p>At first, we directly integrated with the third-party providers and provided support for Facebook, Google, and Twitter. But <strong>we quickly learned that managing these providers required ongoing work to follow their ever-changing APIs<%2fstrong> (I%38#39;m looking at you Facebook). For a startup, that was taking significant resources. A colleague had mentioned <a href=%34http%3a%2f%2fwww.janrain.com%34>Janrain<%2fa>. I was familiar with the company from their very early work %38amp; contributions in the OpenID space. After reading up on their documentation, we really liked the idea of supporting only *one* API and letting Janrain handle the rest, from evolving APIs to adding new <a href=%34%2fsolutions%2fsupported-networks%34>providers<%2fa>. The decision was clear for us and we made the switch rapidly.<%2fp>				
											<p>We quickly became impressed with the <a href=%34%2fproducts%2fjanrain-engage%2ffeatures%34>features Janrain had to offer<%2fa>, like login analytics, and a dashboard to select and edit login network preferences. The ability to track daily logins has proved useful. It allows us to know where to focus our attention for pushing updates to a person%38#39;s activity stream. And because we support Single Sign-On (SSO), we can also track the logins of third-party companies we partner with and see how their daily activity is improving. Some of our partners include <a href=%34http%3a%2f%2fwww.weebly.com%2f%34 target=%34_blank%34>Weebly<%2fa>, <a href=%34http%3a%2f%2fwww.bligoo.com%2f%34 target=%34_blank%34>Bligoo<%2fa>, and <a href=%34http%3a%2f%2fwww.yola.com%2f%34 target=%34_blank%34>Yola<%2fa>.<%2fp>				
											<p>We%38#39;re now supporting more logins than we had ever planned, and that is important, for instance, when the Facebook privacy issue hit the mainstream news, we saw Facebook logins drop, and a handful of other logins picked up, that we wouldn%38#39;t have previously supported.<%2fp>				
											<p style=%34text-align%3a center; %34><img alt=%34%34 src=%34%2fsites%2fdefault%2ffiles%2fsoccer.jpg%34 style=%34width%3a 500px; height%3a 298px; %34 %2f><%2fp>				
											<p>We have a second product line that doesn%38#39;t have support for third-party logins, comparing the two services, I%38#39;ve noticed a few interesting things%3a<%2fp>				
											<ul>				
											<li>More visitors signing in. When we switched to third-party logins with Janrain, <strong>we saw the number of visitors who login increase by over 40%<%2fstrong>!<%2fli>				
											<li><strong>Less time with our support team<%2fstrong>. Previously, we had over 30 people%2fday with login issues that needed to head to a support site. Now with Janrain, <strong>we have not had one support issue due to login<%2fstrong>, issues like forgotten passwords, incorrect emails, expired or conflicting cookies are ting of the past.<%2fli>				
											<%2ful>				
											<p>We%38#39;re continuing to integrate more of the Janrain product line into our services, and in the past few months, I%38#39;ve had a number of colleagues tell me they%38#39;re doing the same.<%2fp>",
